[Please note that the available information is about _Mikrocytos mackini_. According to the OIE's Aquatic Manual, infection of oysters with _Mikrocytos_ is considered to be with _M. mackini_, the causative agent of Denman Island disease.

_M. mackini_ is a protozoan of unknown taxonomic affiliations. Phylogenetic analyses suggested that _M. mackini_ may be a basal eukaryote, but almost certainly is not closely related to other known protistan taxa.

Pacific oyster (_Crassostrea gigas_), eastern oyster (_C. virginica_), European flat oyster (_Ostrea edulis_), and Olympia oyster (_O. lurida_) are oyster species susceptible to infection.

All life stages of oysters after settlement are susceptible to infection. The susceptibility of larvae is not known. Infection can be fatal depending on host and environmental conditions.

Cool temperatures of less than 10 deg C (50 deg F) for 3-4 months seem to be a requirement for disease development. Experimentally exposed oysters held at 15 deg C (59 deg F) for 3 months did not develop the disease until they were transferred and maintained at 10 deg C for an additional 4 months. The annual appearance of the disease only during the spring (March to June) could be explained by the cool temperature requirements for disease development.

Management techniques can be employed by the aquaculture industry to circumvent the impact of _M. mackini_.

For the above and additional background information, including diagnostic methods and references, please refer to Chapter 2.4.8 of the OIE Aquatic Manual, Infection with _M. mackini_. This disease is no longer an OIE listed disease. http://www.oie.int/fileadmin/Home/eng/Health_standards/aahm/current/2.4.08_M_MACKINI.pdf.

Clinical signs of infection include dead and gaping oysters found in the spring. Gross examination may reveal focal lesions predominately of the vesicular connective tissue. These lesions may develop into pustules, abscesses, and ulcerations in the area of the mantle often with corresponding brown scars on the shell. These sings are similar to those of many other diseases affecting shellfish and are, therefore, not pathognomonic of _M. mackini_ (http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Guide-Mikrocytosis.pdf).

_M. mackini_ has not been found in oysters in the UK. (http://www.defra.gov.uk/aahm/files/Guide-Mikrocytosis.pdf).

The causal agent for this particular event was identified as _Mikrocytos mimicus_ a new species of the pathogen of an unlisted disease, hence the reason for it being notified as an emerging disease. Given that it is identified as an emerging disease, the OIE recommends that it be reported to alert and make Member countries aware of the event.

The affected species was the Pacific oyster (_Crassostrea gigas_), impacting primarily adult, market-sized oysters.

For background on the Pacific oyster (_C. gigas_) and its importance in the United Kingdom, see commentaries in ProMED-mail postings 20131030.2030679 and 20131107.2043842.

Pacific oyster (_C. gigas_) photos can be seen at http://eol.org/pages/451579/overview.

The fact that outbreaks of oyster herpesvirus (see ProMED-mail archive number 20131107.2043842) and now _Mikrocytos mimicus_ have been reported recently may be an indication of UK's increased surveillance for diseases in molluscs. - Mod.CRD

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/9t0K.]
